Amend the European Stability Pact
The European Stability Pact, which supports the euro by imposing constraints that determine the size of budget deficits of Union members, is in danger.
Germany, the economic powerhouse of the Union, failed to meet its budgetary commitments to its European partners.
Moreover, she used her political weight to cover the early warning signal of her deficit, established by the European Commission in accordance with the terms of the Stability Pact.
Today it's France that's playing the bad guys.
The second-ranking member of the Union, who was not very enthusiastic, has now officially declared that it cannot fulfill its commitment to reduce the budget deficit, a year after the small Ireland received an official warning regarding its fiscal policies, despite its budget surpluses, and in a very severe manner.
Thus, four years after its signing, the stability pact is a real disaster.
In fact, Europe seems to be very affected by the discussions aimed at eliminating it, as well as those aimed at amending it.
And rightly so: the pact is poorly conceived and its implementation is badly done.
Limiting the deficit to 3% of GDP is arbitrary and ignores the fact that deficits automatically increase when the economy slows down.
Admitting this fact, the architects of the pact worsened the situation by adopting two "ill-conceived" solutions.
They introduced a safety clause allowing any country to suspend its deficit limits in case of a significant recession, but they defined it in such a way that any suspension is virtually impossible in practice.
Concerned that serious slowdowns could undermine the deficit ceiling, they decreed that a normal deficit was equivalent to zero deficit.
Thus, each year, each country must submit a two-year budget forecast demonstrating how the budget balance will be achieved in due time.
Germany's commitment for 2002 was made in 2001, when its economy was developing at a reasonable pace.
The unexpected slowdown prevents Germany from achieving its goals.
The finance minister, Hans Eichel, reasonably decided not to worsen the situation by adopting a contractionary fiscal policy.
The Commission, seeking to position itself as the protector of the pact, intended to issue a warning, but this decision had to be made by real politicians, the Council of Finance Ministers.
No one wanted to embarrass Germany because everyone recognized that they could face the same problem in the future.
Thus, no warning was given.
The situation in France is different.
During election periods, politicians inevitably make promises, including reducing tax burdens.
In a country where the tax burden is significant, it is not only a matter of political intelligence, but also of economic intelligence, as long as budget expenditures are also reduced.
However, France is also a country where everyone benefits from certain privileges funded by the state, and as a result, budget cuts are definitely poorly perceived.
Thus, France cannot achieve its objectives, and the Commission has expressed its frustration.
But France has become a master at defying the laws of the Union.
Political maneuvering will inevitably follow.
Economists and cynics are not much surprised.
The objective of the pact, to establish a fiscal discipline within countries sharing the same currency, is entirely acceptable.
However, the loss of control over their national monetary policy, the members of the Union no longer have access to only one macroeconomic tool: fiscal policies.
The challenge is therefore to combine long-term discipline with short-term flexibility.
Just like promising to go on a diet before a big party, this challenge is not easy to balance.
The Stability Pact is too rudimentary and technocratic: the objective of 3% imposed by the Brussels bureaucrats cannot bind politicians in office.
The solution must be found elsewhere.
Fortunately, we don't have to look very far.
Monetary policy faces the same challenge.
It must stabilize long-term prices while remaining sufficiently flexible in the short term to manage economic cycles.
Over the past ten years, monetary policy experienced real success.
The recipe is the same everywhere: it suffices to delegate this policy to a competent group, the central bank, by granting it the necessary political independence and a clear and well-defined mandate.
Knowing that any misstep will need to be addressed in the future, it's up to him to show good sense.
This proved to be one of the major improvements in the monetary field in recent years.
The same approach should work for fiscal policy.
Some, of course, fear losing it in democracy.
It is essential to understand that fiscal policy serves two very different purposes.
The first is structural and redistributive, and concerns the importance of the budget and its detailed structure, both in terms of expenditures and revenues.
Decisions on these matters cannot be delegated and must remain in the hands of elected governments, subject to parliamentary approval and oversight.
The second is macroeconomic: it involves defining the budget balance to manage fluctuation cycles.
It differs little from monetary policy and can be delegated to an independent body.
Thus, Europe's task is clear.
Each country must regain full control over its fiscal policies but delegate its macroeconomic components, decisions on deficits or surpluses, to an independent Fiscal Policy Committee, whose long-term objective is the stabilization (or reduction, for some countries) of public debt.
To ensure the result, the status of such a committee and its mandates must be the subject of a consensus within the Union, without any interference from Brussels, without any arbitrary rules, without any political decision-making, but simply by relying on common sense.
